cff-version: 1.2.0
title: "ITU and Cryptography: A Single-Axiom Framework for Quantum and Post-Quantum Information Protection"
message: "If you use this work, please cite it as below."
type: software
authors:
  - family-names: Terada
    given-names: Munehiro
    affiliation: Roboken
    email: munehiro.terada@roboken2.com
abstract: >
  We apply the Information-Theoretic Unification (ITU) framework
  (Terada 2026, DOI 10.5281/zenodo.20109210) to cryptography. The
  ITU axiom dS = d<K> simultaneously governs noise correction
  (quantum error correction, QECC) and adversary protection
  (cryptography) - these are dual applications of the same
  information-protection principle. This paper develops the
  consequences across the full cryptographic landscape.
  Phase 51 establishes the ITU foundation: Shannon's perfect
  secrecy theorem (OTP), BB84 information-theoretic security,
  and post-quantum computational security all follow from the
  ITU axiom applied to adversary-resilient code design.
  Phase 52 analyses BB84 in detail with photon loss and the
  decoy-state protocol, projecting practical key rates over
  10-500 km fibre links and ~200 km practical distance limit.
  We propose a naive ITU enhancement (embed the [[5,1,3]] code
  in transmitted photons) and report a HONEST NEGATIVE FINDING:
  the naive embedding underperforms standard BB84 because the
  5x overhead dominates the loss-recovery gain. This refines the
  ITU prescription: protective code embedding must respect
  channel-specific overhead trade-offs.
  Phase 53 covers lattice-based post-quantum cryptography
  (CRYSTALS-Kyber, CRYSTALS-Dilithium, NIST 2024 standards).
  We implement a toy LWE KEM and verify exponential brute-force
  scaling. Kyber-1024 provides ~256/240-bit (classical/quantum)
  security, future-proof through the 2050s. We propose an
  "ITU 3-tier" cryptographic framework: Tier 1 classical, Tier
  2 quantum-safe (PQC + QKD), Tier 3 ASI-safe (Phi_ITU embedded
  protocols). Serial application yields combined 768-bit
  security against adversaries up to ASI.
  Phase 54 synthesises into a 2024-2040 migration roadmap with
  cost estimates by organisation type, 10 falsifiable
  predictions, and policy recommendations at national,
  corporate, and individual levels. Central thesis: under ITU,
  cryptography is the DUAL of QECC, both governed by dS = d<K>,
  and a 3-tier defence in depth is the optimal response to the
  ASI-era threat landscape. This is Tier 1 paper #3 in the ITU
  programme, completing the engineering triangle of Quantum
  Computing (10.5281/zenodo.20139391), Machine Consciousness
  (10.5281/zenodo.20150501), and Cryptography.
